    "Let me analyze the mapped transformation to identify the reaction center.\n\nLooking at the SMIRKS reaction:\n\nReactants: [H:20][O:21]S(=O)(=O)C1=CC=C(C=C1)C.CCOC(=O)C1(C(CCC2(C1CC(=[O:10])CC2=O)C#N)C)C(=O)OCC.CO\n\nProducts: [H:20][O+:10]=C1CC2C(CCC(C2(C(=O)OCC)C(=O)OCC)C)(C(=O)C1)C#N.CC1=CC=C(C=C1)S(=O)(=O)[O-:21].CO\n\nKey observations from atom mapping:\n\n1. [H:20] is attached to [O:21] in reactants (sulfonic acid OH) and remains attached to [O:21] in products\n2. [O:10] is a ketone oxygen (=O) in reactants, but becomes [O+:10] in products bonded to [H:20] - forming an enol/oxocarbenium\n3. [O:21] goes from being part of -OH on sulfur to being [O-:21] on sulfur (sulfonate)\n\nSo the reaction center involves:\n- The ketone C=O (where O is mapped as :10) gets protonated by the sulfonic acid\n- The sulfonic acid loses its proton to the ketone oxygen\n- The sulfonate becomes the conjugate base\n\nThis is an acid-catalyzed enolization / protonation of a ketone by p-toluenesulfonic acid.\n\nThe reaction center: The ketone oxygen (O:10) is protonated by the sulfonic acid (O:21-H:20), converting C=[O:10] to C=[O+:10]-[H:20] and converting [H:20][O:21] to [O-:21].\n\nLet me be more precise about the bond changes:\n- Bond broken: O:21-H:20 (in TsOH)\n- Bond formed: O:10-H:20 (proton transfer to ketone oxygen)\n- Bond order change: C=[O:10] → C=[O+:10] (formal charge change on O:10)\n- Formal charge change on O:21: neutral → negative (O-)\n\nThe reaction center is the proton transfer from TsOH to the ketone oxygen.\n\nIn terms of a compact reaction edit summary:\n- Break O:21-H:20 bond\n- Form O:10-H:20 bond\n- O:10 gains positive charge (protonation)\n- O:21 gains negative charge (deprotonation)\n\nLet me format this as a reaction_edit_summary."
